the extracellular membrane interface and extends further into the extracellular space about four additional helical turns while TM2 extends beyond the intracellular membrane interface into the cytoplasm (Figure 2A). TM1 and TM2 within the b4 monomer form an extensive interface with mostly hydrophobic interactions (Figure 2B). The extended C-terminal part of TM2 also interacts with the N-loop through a few hydrogen bonds (Figure 2B).
The well-ordered EC domain, which connects TM1 and TM2, contains mostly b strands (bA-bE, bH-bI), two short a helices (aF-aG) and loops in between (Figure 2A and C and Figure 2—figure supplement 1A). The structure is held together by four disulfide bonds (Figure 2C). The b4 EC domain also contains two predicted N-glycosylation sites, with one of them conserved among all the b subunits (Figure 2C and Figure 2—figure supplement 1A). Glycosylation at these two predicted sites were confirmed with tandem ms/ms and extra density near both sites was observed in the final map, most likely representing the sugars. Glycosylation was shown to regulate the sensitivity of Slo1-b4 to iberiotoxin and also modify other biophysical properties of Slo1-b1 (Jin et al., 2002; Hagen and Sanders, 2006). In the open Slo1-b4 model, these two glycosylation sites are located at the outer periphery of the EC domain, far from the b4/b4 or a/b4 interfaces (Figure 2C). Therefore, the structure does not obviously explain the functional effects of these modifications. We note that proteins in this study were expressed using a glycosylation-deficient strain that produces smaller sugar groups. We cannot rule out the possibility that these sugars under physiological conditions might form carbohydrate-carbohydrate or carbohydrate-protein interactions not observed in the current structural model. The secondary structural elements as well as the four disulfide bonds match a recently published NMR structure of the extracellular loop of human b4 (Wang et al., 2018). However, our Slo1-b4 complex structure exhibits a completely different tertiary structure of the EC domain than that proposed on the basis of NMR experiments. Based on a hypothetical Slo1-b4 model constructed from NMR titration and the b4 EC solution structure, N123 on b4 was suggested to be critical for regulating Slo1 gating through interactions with E264 on the turret of the a subunit upon Ca2+ binding (Wang et al., 2018). The distance between sidechains of these two residues was

