nucleotide binding proteins (such as exosome complex component RRP45 and translation initiation factor 2 g subunit), which contain some of the b strands, and certain toxins (such as pertussis toxin and subtilase cytotoxin), which contain much shorter helices and loops. The physiological importance of this EC domain must await further study (see Discussion).
The stoichiometry of a and b subunits was assumed generally to be 1:1. Evidence of sub 1:1 stoichiometry emerged from analysis of co-expression in oocytes (Wang et al., 2002) as well as in native tissues (Solaro et al., 1995; Ding et al., 1998; Kuntamallappanavar et al., 2017). It was proposed that a Slo1 channel can contain zero to four b subunits, with each b subunit incrementally influencing channel gating properties (Wang et al., 2002). In the Slo1-b4 complex structure, b4 binds to the a subunit with 1:1 subunit stoichiometry (i.e. four b4 subunits per tetramer of a subunits) (Figures 1B and 2D–E). The four b4 subunits form extensive interfaces with neighboring EC domains, encompassing a buried area of ~907 A˚ 2/monomer (Figure 2D–G). The protein sample used for EM studies was produced by overexpressing b4, thus we cannot rule out the possibility that a sub 1:1 b:a complex could exist under physiological conditions. However, the structure would predict a more stable conformation upon tetramer formation because the EC domain, which interacts extensively with itself, makes only minimal contact with the a subunit (Figures 1B and 2D–G).
Chemical nature of interfaces between b4 and a
Many biochemical and molecular biological studies have analyzed interactions between Slo1 and b subunits using, for example, disulfide crosslinking and TOXCAT assays (Liu et al., 2008; Wu et al., 2009; Liu et al., 2010; Morera et al., 2012; Wu et al., 2013). TM1 was predicted to be in the vicinity of S1 and S2 on the VSD (Liu et al., 2008; Wu et al., 2009; Liu et al., 2010; Wu et al., 2013) and direct interactions between TM1 of b2 and S1 of the VSD were found using the TOXCAT assay (Morera et al., 2012). In our Slo1-b4 structure, b4 associates with the a subunit almost exclusively through the two TM helices (Figure 3A). The TM1 segment near the outer leaflet of the membrane contacts the transmembrane domain (TMD) from one a subunit (‘a1’) through hydrophobic interactions with sidechains from S1 and the pore helix (PH), while at the same time interacting with sidechains from S6 and the turret of a contiguous a subunit (‘a2’) (Figure 3A–B). Notably, lipid molecules also contribute to these interfaces (Figure 3A–B). The TM1 segment near the inner leaflet acyl chain region mostly contacts S3 of a2 and several ordered lipid molecules through hydrophobic interactions (Figure 3C). The bottom of TM1, near the intracellular membrane interface, makes contacts with multiple regions of the a subunit including the S2-S3 linker and S0 from a2, the S6-RCK1 linker from a1 and phospholipid headgroups through hydrogen bonds (Figure 3C). With the same TOXCAT assay, no direct association with the a subunit was detected for TM2, the EC domain, or the C-terminus of b and it was thus suggested that there are no strong interactions between TM2 and S0 despite the nearness predicted from the disulfide crosslinking experiments (Liu et al., 2008; Wu et al., 2009; Liu et al., 2010; Morera et al., 2012; Wu et al., 2013). Our structure shows that the TM2 outer leaflet segment only interacts with a2. Furthermore, this interface is purely mediated by lipid molecules forming a hydrophobic core with TM2 sidechains (Figure 3A–B). The TM2 inner leaflet segment forms an extensive protein:protein interface with S0 and S3 from a2 (Figure 3A and C). The residues of b4 directly involved in the a/b association turn out to be fairly conserved among b1-b4 (Figure 2—figure supplement 1A). Therefore, it would seem likely that b1-b4 subunits all bind to Slo1 in a similar fashion. Furthermore, Slo1 residues involved in these specific interactions appear to be conserved between Slo1 and Slo3, which would explain why all members of the b subunit family also physically associate with Slo3 (Figure 2—figure supplement 1B) (Yang et al., 2009). We emphasize the general observation that lipid molecules make significant contributions to the a/b interfaces at both the inner and outer membrane leaflets, suggesting they are an integral part of the Slo1 a-b4 channel complex (Figure 3).
In the open a-b4 model, the N-loop preceding TM1 is located adjacent to the S6-RCK1 linker and the aC helix of the RCK1 N-lobe, making short and long-range interactions between these regions likely. T11 of b4 is less than 5 A˚ away from D173 in the S2-S3 loop of the a subunit; the E12 sidechain of b4 is about 5.5 A˚ away from R329 in the S6-RCK1 linker and is also in the vicinity of W176 on S3 and H409 on the aC helix.
Wang et. al. suggested that the EC domain of b1 might interact with the extracellular side of the Slo1 VSD, as mutations in that region caused appreciable changes in Slo1 gating (Gruslova et al., 2012). The Slo1-b4 complex structure shows essentially no direct association between the b4 EC

